// C2: Acting Components
instance MotorGearTransmissionSystem : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Primary actuation unit comprising a permanent magnet synchronous motor (PMSM) and cycloidal gear transmission for high-precision motion control in the MABI MAX 100 serial industrial robot's first axis. Regulates motion via closed-loop feedback with safety constraints implied through controller intervention."
]

instance ControllerUnit : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Dedicated controller managing the motor-gear transmission mechanism for robotic operations, implementing closed-loop feedback to regulate motion and prevent over-actuation or mechanical failure."
]

// C3: Physical sensing components
instance AngularDisplacementEncoderFirstAxis : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Position encoder deployed on the first axis motor-gear transmission system to measure angular displacement with high precision for real-time feedback to the controller. Part of two-encoder configuration per drive with MQTT-based time-series data streaming."
    DTDFVocab:producedData AngularDisplacementDataFirstAxis
]

instance AngularDisplacementEncoderSecondAxis : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Position encoder deployed on the second axis motor-gear transmission system to measure angular displacement with high precision for real-time feedback to the controller. Part of two-encoder configuration per drive with MQTT-based time-series data streaming."
    DTDFVocab:producedData AngularDisplacementDataSecondAxis
]

instance MotorCurrentSensorFirstAxis : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Current sensor integrated with the first axis motor to measure input current for torque estimation and closed-loop control validation. Part of automated one-way data aggregation system."
    DTDFVocab:producedData MotorCurrentDataFirstAxis
]

instance GearboxFrictionSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Sensor embedded in the cycloidal gear transmission system to monitor friction characteristics during operation, enabling multi-physics analysis for control accuracy optimization."
    DTDFVocab:producedData GearboxFrictionData
]

// C4: Physical-to-virtual interaction
instance AngularDisplacementDataFirstAxis : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom AngularDisplacementEncoderFirstAxis
]

instance AngularDisplacementDataSecondAxis : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom AngularDisplacementEncoderSecondAxis
]

instance MotorCurrentDataFirstAxis : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom MotorCurrentSensorFirstAxis
]

instance GearboxFrictionData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom GearboxFrictionSensor
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance DigitalShadowDataAggregationLayer : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Foundational data abstraction layer implementing the Digital Shadow Reference Model (Kritzinger et al.) for automated, one-way data aggregation from physical components to digital representations. Enables contextual data enrichment for future analytics."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataProcessingEnabler
]

instance SysMLInternalBlockDiagram : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "SysML IBD representing component interfaces and composition for the MABI MAX 100 robot system, including motor-gear transmission and sensor-actuator relationships. Used for structural and behavioral validation."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SysMLModelingTool
]

instance SimulinkFrictionModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Executable friction model developed in MathWorks Simulink for the first axis, enabling dynamic behavior simulation and closed-loop validation of multi-physics characteristics."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulationEngine
]

instance AngularDisplacementData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Structured time-series data representing angular displacement measurements from position encoders, transmitted via MQTT protocol with low-latency requirements for real-time control applications."
    DTDFVocab:fromData AngularDisplacementDataFirstAxis, AngularDisplacementDataSecondAxis
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataProcessingEnabler
]

instance MotorCurrentData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Floating-point numerical data representing input current measurements from motor sensors, used for torque estimation and energy consumption analysis in the digital twin."
    DTDFVocab:fromData MotorCurrentDataFirstAxis
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataProcessingEnabler
]

instance GearboxFrictionData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Contextual data traces capturing friction characteristics in the cycloidal gear transmission system, enabling multi-physics analysis for control accuracy optimization."
    DTDFVocab:fromData GearboxFrictionData
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataProcessingEnabler
]

instance MechanicalWearMonitoringData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Passive state tracking data of mechanical wear parameters collected from operational traces, serving as baseline for predictive maintenance analysis."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataProcessingEnabler
]

// C11: Enablers
instance SysMLModelingTool : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "IBM Rational Software Architect or compatible tool implementing SysML v1.7 for multi-layered modeling (requirements → logical architecture → physical layer) following RFLP methodology. Enables component-connector perspective modeling."
    DTDFVocab:enables BaselineMonitoringService
]

instance SimulationEngine : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MathWorks MATLAB Simulink environment for creating executable friction models and dynamic behavior simulations of the first axis transmission system."
    DTDFVocab:enables FrictionModelingService
]

instance DataProcessingEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Software framework implementing automated data aggregation and preprocessing pipelines for contextual data traces, enabling real-time abstraction and consistency with structured models."
    DTDFVocab:enables DataAggregationService, BaselineMonitoringService
]

instance MQTTProtocolStack : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Low-latency, high-throughput MQTT protocol implementation for real-time sensor data streaming from physical components to digital twin infrastructure."
    DTDFVocab:enables DataAggregationService
]

// C6: Services
instance DataAggregationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Passive, one-way automated service collecting contextual data traces (angular displacement, motor current, gearbox friction) from physical robot components via MQTT for real-time digital abstraction."
    DTDFVocab:provides ContextualDataInsight
]

instance BaselineMonitoringService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Passive state tracking service providing continuous monitoring of operational parameters (mechanical wear, energy consumption) without autonomous intervention, serving as baseline for future analytics."
    DTDFVocab:provides MechanicalWearInsight, EnergyConsumptionInsight
]

instance FrictionModelingService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Simulation-driven service enabling multi-physics friction analysis of the cycloidal gear transmission system using Simulink models for control accuracy optimization."
    DTDFVocab:provides FrictionCharacteristicsInsight
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance ContextualDataInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Aggregated contextual insights derived from time-series sensor data enabling continuous multi-physics-aware analysis of system dynamics and operational behavior."
]

instance MechanicalWearInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Predictive maintenance insights generated from passive monitoring of mechanical wear parameters, enabling proactive maintenance planning."
]

instance EnergyConsumptionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Operational efficiency insights derived from motor current data analysis, supporting energy consumption optimization strategies."
]

instance FrictionCharacteristicsInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Multi-physics friction analysis results enabling joint friction identification and control accuracy optimization for the robot's first axis."
]

instance ControlAccuracyOptimizationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated optimization action derived from friction modeling insights to improve closed-loop control performance of the motor-gear transmission system."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

// C1: Environment
instance MABIMAX100RobotEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:contains MotorGearTransmissionSystem, ControllerUnit, AngularDisplacementEncoderFirstAxis, AngularDisplacementEncoderSecondAxis, MotorCurrentSensorFirstAxis, GearboxFrictionSensor
]

instance DigitalTwinInfrastructure : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:contains DigitalShadowDataAggregationLayer, SysMLInternalBlockDiagram, SimulinkFrictionModel, AngularDisplacementData, MotorCurrentData, GearboxFrictionData, MechanicalWearMonitoringData
]

// C5: Components
instance FirstAxisMotorGearTransmission : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Physical component representing the first axis of the MABI MAX 100 robot comprising PMSM motor and cycloidal gear transmission with integrated sensors for high-precision machining tasks."
    base:isContainedIn MABIMAX100RobotEnvironment
]

instance SecondAxisMotorGearTransmission : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Physical component representing the second axis of the MABI MAX 100 robot with similar motor-gear transmission configuration as the first axis for multi-axis motion control."
    base:isContainedIn MABIMAX100RobotEnvironment
]

instance ManufacturingAutomationSystem : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Higher-level component representing the complete manufacturing automation system incorporating the MABI MAX 100 robot with its digital twin infrastructure for process optimization."
    base:isContainedIn DigitalTwinInfrastructure
]

// Added missing environment relationships
instance MABIMAX100Robot : DTDFVocab:SystemUnderStudy [
    base:desc "MABI MAX 100 serial industrial robot system under study for digital twin implementation."
    DTDFVocab:hasEnvironment MABIMAX100RobotEnvironment
]

instance ManufacturingSystem : DTDFVocab:SystemUnderStudy [
    base:desc "Complete manufacturing automation system including the MABI MAX 100 robot and its digital twin infrastructure."
    DTDFVocab:hasEnvironment DigitalTwinInfrastructure
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system described in the provided documents does not explicitly detail synchronization frequencies, time scales for services, latency requirements, or temporal granularity needs. However, the context implies that **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies (e.g., SysML, ADLs like AADL, or simulation tools such as MathWorks Simulink) are used to model system behavior, which inherently requires precise temporal alignment between physical and digital components. For example, **SysML state machines** or **MontiArc Automaton** may enforce discrete or continuous time scales depending on the application domain. The documents do not specify exact frequencies (e.g., Hz, ms, or seconds) or latency constraints, but the integration of **simulation tools** (e.g., Simulink) suggests real-time or near-real-time synchronization is assumed for dynamic system behaviors. No concrete temporal metrics (e.g., <100ms latency) are provided, thus leaving this aspect abstracted to domain-specific implementations."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system’s orchestration is framed within **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** paradigms, leveraging **architecture patterns** from ADLs (e.g., **component-connector models** in ACME or AADL) and **behavioral modeling** (e.g., state machines in SysML v1.7 or MontiArc Automaton). The **component integration** is achieved through **heterogeneous toolchains**, combining ADLs with simulation tools (e.g., Simulink) or general-purpose languages (e.g., C++, Java). **Resource management** is implied via **modular decomposition** (e.g., RFLP layers), where each layer (requirements, functions, logic, physics) abstracts responsibilities. **System-wide coordination** is not explicitly detailed but is inferred from the **integration of multiple modeling notations** (e.g., SysML for architecture + Simulink for dynamics), suggesting a **hybrid orchestration** approach. The document does not specify **real-time coordination protocols** (e.g., DDS, ROS) or **cloud-edge deployment strategies**, leaving these aspects to domain-specific implementations."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "
The lifecycle of a Digital Twin (DT) system is structured through **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies, encompassing multiple abstraction layers: **requirements, functional architecture, logical architecture, and product/technical layers**. These stages are governed by methodologies such as **RFLP (Requirements, Functions, Logics, Physics)**, **OOSEM**, **SPES**, or **SMArDT**, which systematically decompose system complexity. The lifecycle transitions between phases involve **architecture description languages (ADLs)** like **ACME, AADL, MontiArc, or SysML Internal Block Diagrams (IBDs)** to model components, interfaces, connectors, and composition. Behavior modeling integrates **state machines (SysML v1.7)** or **MontiArc Automaton**, while detailed behavior is further refined using **MathWorks Simulink, simulation tools, or general-purpose languages (C++, Java)**. Lifecycle governance ensures integration of **heterogeneous stakeholder perspectives** and **modeling notations** across tools, emphasizing **version control, traceability, and iterative refinement** to maintain consistency and accuracy throughout development, deployment, and operational phases.
"
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin’s **model fidelity** is validated through **comparative analysis of simulated vs. measured data**, where deviations are analyzed to assess accuracy. **Uncertainty quantification** is implicitly addressed via the **sensor arrangement** (dual encoders) to reduce **backlash and positional uncertainty**, though explicit error metrics (e.g., RMSE, confidence intervals) are not provided. **Quality assurance processes** are inferred from **MBSE methodologies**, including **SysML-based verification** and **Simulink-driven validation**, though no formalized error detection/correction mechanisms (e.g., Kalman filters, machine learning-based anomaly detection) are documented. The system relies on **control-loop feedback** (e.g., via SINUMERIK 840D sl) for runtime fidelity adjustments, but **no explicit validation protocols** (e.g., ISO/IEC standards, certification frameworks) are referenced."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The **technical network infrastructure** for this Digital Twin system is not explicitly detailed in the provided documents. However, the **MQTT protocol** is mentioned as a means for streaming data from physical to digital components, implying it may also be used for communication between system components. No further specifications regarding network topology (e.g., mesh, star), bandwidth requirements, latency constraints, redundancy mechanisms, or security protocols (e.g., TLS, VPN) are provided."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The deployment infrastructure for this Digital Twin system is grounded in **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies, which utilize **architecture description languages (ADLs)** like SysML for defining system components, interfaces, and interconnections. The system may leverage **heterogeneous tools** (e.g., MathWorks Simulink for behavior modeling, general-purpose languages like C++ or Java for implementation) to ensure interoperability. However, specific deployment platforms (cloud/edge/on-premise), computational/storage requirements, scalability mechanisms, or availability assurances (e.g., redundancy, failover) are **not in Document**. The system must accommodate **multiple abstraction layers** (requirements, functional/logical architecture, physical layer) as per MBSE practices, but no explicit hosting environment (e.g., containerization, orchestration) is referenced."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system integrates with **external systems via MQTT-based streaming protocols** for real-time sensor data acquisition, as explicitly stated in the context: *'We have access to time series of all sensors, which are streamed via MQTT.'* Horizontal integration adheres to **enterprise interoperability standards** implied by MBSE methodologies, though no specific protocols (e.g., OPC UA, REST APIs) or **enterprise service buses (ESB)** are mentioned beyond MQTT for sensor data. The system integrates with **heterogeneous stakeholders and perspectives** (e.g., requirements, functional, and physical layers) via **MBSE toolchains** (e.g., SysML, Simulink), ensuring **cross-domain compatibility**. **No explicit integration patterns** (e.g., API gateways, event-driven architectures) are documented, but the **MQTT-based data flow** and **ADL toolchains** facilitate **plug-and-play interoperability** with external systems. Dependencies on external systems are limited to **sensor data ingestion** and **simulation tool compatibility** (e.g., Simulink models)."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system incorporates **safety cell restrictions** to ensure operational safety, where the **safety cell of the robot** (as referenced in [44]) explicitly restricts the **maximum working range** to predefined boundaries, mitigating collision risks. The system leverages **MQTT protocol** ([52]) for communication, which inherently supports **QoS (Quality of Service) levels** (0, 1, 2) to prioritize critical safety-related data transmissions, ensuring timely response to emergency conditions. While no explicit **access control mechanisms** or **authentication systems** are detailed in the provided documents, the **Digital Shadow methodology** ([42]) implies a structured data flow where **conformance relations** ([41]) could theoretically enforce role-based access control (RBAC) for sensitive operations. However, **no formal threat mitigation strategies**, **fail-safe mechanisms**, or **risk assessment frameworks** (e.g., IEC 62443) are explicitly described in the context of the Digital Twin system. The **Asset Administration Shell (AAS)** ([46], [47], [50])—though referenced in broader Industry 4.0 contexts—is not directly tied to safety-critical system considerations in the provided documents. The **functional mockup interface (FMI)** ([51]) for simulation models does not address security or safety but ensures **interoperability** between tools, which could indirectly support safety validation workflows. Overall, the documents emphasize **operational safety boundaries** (e.g., robot safety cells) and **communication protocols** (e.g., MQTT QoS) but lack detailed **cybersecurity protocols**, **fail-safe designs**, or **compliance frameworks** for safety-critical systems."
]